    {
      "content": "Overview",
      "pos": [
        646,
        654
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Microsoft Azure virtual machines (VMs) with SQL Server can help lower the cost of a high availability and disaster recovery (HADR) database solution.",
      "pos": [
        656,
        805
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Most SQL Server HADR solutions are supported in Azure virtual machines, both as  Azure-only  and as hybrid solutions.",
      "pos": [
        806,
        923
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In an Azure-only solution, the entire HADR system runs in  Azure.",
      "pos": [
        924,
        989
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In a hybrid configuration, part of the solution runs in Azure and the other part runs on-premises in your organization.",
      "pos": [
        990,
        1109
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The flexibility of the Azure environment enables you to move partially or completely to  Azure to satisfy the budget and HADR requirements of your SQL Server database systems.",
      "pos": [
        1110,
        1285
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Understanding the need for an HADR solution",
      "pos": [
        1290,
        1333
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is up to you to ensure that your database system possesses the HADR capabilities that the service-level agreement (SLA) requires.",
      "pos": [
        1335,
        1467
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The fact that Azure provides high availability mechanisms, such as service healing for cloud services and failure recovery detection for the Virtual Machines, does not itself guarantee you can meet the desired SLA.",
      "pos": [
        1468,
        1682
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These mechanisms protect the high availability of the VMs but not the high availability of SQL Server running inside the VMs.",
      "pos": [
        1684,
        1809
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is possible for the SQL Server instance to fail while the VM is online and healthy.",
      "pos": [
        1810,
        1896
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Moreover, even the high availability mechanisms provided by Azure allow for  downtime of the VMs due to events such as recovery from software or hardware failures and operating system upgrades.",
      "pos": [
        1897,
        2090
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition, Geo Redundant Storage (GRS) in Azure, which is implemented with a feature called geo-replication, may not be an adequate disaster recovery solution for your databases.",
      "pos": [
        2092,
        2272
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Because geo-replication sends data asynchronously, recent updates can be lost in the event of disaster.",
      "pos": [
        2273,
        2376
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "More information regarding geo-replication limitations are covered in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Geo-replication not supported for data and log files on separate disks<ept id=\"p1\">](#geo-replication-support)</ept> section.",
      "pos": [
        2378,
        2559
      ]
    },
