    {
      "content": "WSFC cluster behavior in Azure networking",
      "pos": [
        10507,
        10548
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The non-RFC-compliant DHCP service in Azure can cause the creation of certain WSFC cluster configurations to fail, due to the cluster network name being assigned a duplicate IP address, such as the same IP address as one of the cluster nodes.",
      "pos": [
        10550,
        10792
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is an issue when you implement AlwaysOn Availability Groups, which depends on the WSFC feature.",
      "pos": [
        10793,
        10893
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Consider the scenario when a two-node cluster is created and brought online:",
      "pos": [
        10895,
        10971
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The cluster comes online, then NODE1 requests a dynamically assigned IP address for the cluster network name.",
      "pos": [
        10976,
        11085
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "No IP address other than NODE1’s own IP address is given by the DHCP service, since the DHCP service recognizes that the request comes from NODE1 itself.",
      "pos": [
        11090,
        11243
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Windows detects that a duplicate address is assigned both to NODE1 and to the cluster network name, and the default cluster group fails to come online.",
      "pos": [
        11248,
        11399
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The default cluster group moves to NODE2, which treats NODE1’s IP address as the cluster IP address and brings the default cluster group online.",
      "pos": [
        11404,
        11548
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When NODE2 attempts to establish connectivity with NODE1, packets directed at NODE1 never leave NODE2 because it resolves NODE1’s IP address to itself.",
      "pos": [
        11553,
        11704
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "NODE2 cannot establish connectivity with NODE1, then loses quorum and shuts down the cluster.",
      "pos": [
        11705,
        11798
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the meantime, NODE1 can send packets to NODE2, but NODE2 cannot reply.",
      "pos": [
        11803,
        11876
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "NODE1 loses quorum and shuts down the cluster.",
      "pos": [
        11877,
        11923
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This scenario can be avoided by assigning an unused static IP address, such as a link-local IP address like 169.254.1.1, to the cluster network name in order to bring the cluster network name online.",
      "pos": [
        11925,
        12124
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To simplify this process, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Configuring Windows Failover Cluster in Azure for AlwaysOn Availability Groups<ept id=\"p1\">](http://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/14776.configuring-windows-failover-cluster-in-windows-azure-for-alwayson-availability-groups.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        12125,
